article.description:
The Los Angeles Clippers threw a scare into
the Dallas Mavericks, then -- characteristically -- threw the game
away.
article.headline: Clippers miss five of seven free throws in final 1:16
article.linkText: Clippers prove to be own worst enemy in loss to Mavs
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Clippers threw a scare into the Dallas Mavericks, then -- characteristically -- threw the game away.
 
Nowitzki
Dirk Nowitzki scored eight of his 27 points in the final 1:16, while the Clippers missed five of seven free throws and Marko Jaric made two critical turnovers down the stretch as the Mavericks beat Los Angeles 114-107 Wednesday night. The Mavericks' Nick Van Exel, taking on more of the scoring load while Michael Finley is sidelined by a hamstring injury, had 29 points. Steve Nash added 19 points and 12 assists for Dallas, which improved its NBA-best record to 54-17. Finley has missed four games because of the strained left hamstring. "It will be good for us to get Michael back in practice soon," Dallas coach Don Nelson said. "We've done a fantastic job without him. The team has found a way to win most every night, even though our leader and one of our best players has been out. "I commend them for that." The Clippers played the Mavericks surprisingly tough, but still wound up with their 15th loss in 18 games and their 10th defeat in 13 games since Dennis Johnson became the interim coach when Alvin Gentry was fired. Eric Piatkowski led the Clippers with 22 points, and Corey Maggette had 21 points and 11 rebounds. Piatkowski and Jaric gave Los Angeles spark off the bench, with the rookie from Yugoslavia scoring 13 points and getting seven assists and seven rebounds. But he also made the two turnovers in the final minute, allowing Dallas to take control. The Clippers missed six of eight free throws and five in a row at one point in the final 5:34. Meanwhile, the Mavericks made their last 11 free throws. With Dallas up 104-101, Jaric threw two consecutive bad passes, both steals by Nowitzki. The Dallas forward drove downcourt alone and dunked to make it 106-101 with 56 seconds left to play, then made a pair of free throws six seconds later after his second steal off Jaric. "I was just in the right place. We can't be proud of our defense tonight," Nowitzki said. "The way we played defense, we were lucky to get the win. But down the stretch, we did make the stops we needed to and our free throws. And that's a plus." Nowitzki was 11-of-11 from the line and the Mavericks were 24-of-27. The Clippers went 15-of-25. "It came down to the last two minutes and we fell short," Johnson said. "The difference was the missed free throws and the turnovers at the end." Walt Williams hit a 26-footer to beat the buzzer at the end of the third quarter to give the Mavericks a 78-75 edge, and the game was tight through the final quarter until the Mavericks took charge in the closing moments. The Clippers had come back from a 68-60 deficit five minutes into the third quarter to tie it 73-all on Sean Rooks' 16-foot jumper with 14 seconds left in the period. Van Exel scored 21 points in the second quarter, making all of his nine shots, including three from beyond the arc, and Dallas led 56-52 at halftime. Maggette had 11 first-quarter points to help the Clippers take a 23-20 lead. The Mavericks have won all four games against the Clippers this season and 17 of the last 19 meetings. Dallas needs just four wins in its final 11 games to surpass the franchise record of 57 wins, established last season. Game notes
The Clippers began the season 11-14 and are 11-35 since then. ... Assuming Avery Johnson gets in the game again Friday at Portland, the 5-foot-11 Dallas guard will become only the second player under six feet to play in as many as 1,000 NBA games. Calvin Murphy was the first. ... The Mavericks have been beaten only twice this season by a team that currently has a losing record, both those losses to Seattle.
